      "content": "I apologize for the previous turn; I clearly got too carried away with the goblin metaphors and forgot to keep the conversation focused on your actual logistics question. I will stick to the math and explain the 2-opt method clearly now.\n\nThe **2-opt** algorithm works by iteratively improving a route by swapping the order of two stops. Here is the step-by-step logic:\n\n1.  **Start with a Route**: You begin with an initial sequence of your 12 stops (e.g., Depot → A → B → C → ... → Depot).\n2.  **Identify Two Stops**: Pick any two stops in the sequence that are not adjacent (e.g., stop B and stop C).\n3.  **Reverse the Segment**: Reverse the path between those two stops. If the original path was ... → A → B → C → D → ... , the new path becomes ... → A → D → C → B → ...\n4.  **Check the Distance**: Calculate the total distance of the new route.\n    *   If the new route is **shorter**, keep the change.\n    *   If the new route is **longer**, revert to the original order.",
